Methodology 3

 Data Preparation
 The data cleaning process involved handling missing values, standardizing formats, removing duplicates, correcting inconsistencies. This preparation ensured that the data was structured, enriched, and optimized for predictive modeling and visualization.





Model Selection

 A predictive modeling approach was applied to forecast maintenance needs and plant efficiency. A regression-based model was chosen as it can effectively capture the relationship between variables such as plant age, energy source, and maintenance history. The independent variables, including maintenance probability, energy type, and capacity, have complex, non-linear interactions with the dependent variables, like maintenance costs and plant performance. This model is adept at identifying patterns within large datasets, enabling accurate predictions without extensive data cleaning. Its ability to handle diverse data types and relationships makes it ideal for predicting maintenance requirements, helping optimize plant operations, reduce downtime, and enhance overall plant efficiency.





Model Development


The XGBClassifier model was trained and optimized using Power Plant data. The dataset was split into training and testing sets. The training set enabled the model to identify patterns, while the testing set assessed its ability to generalize to unseen data. This approach helps prevent overfitting, ensuring the model doesn’t perform well only on the training data but also on new, unseen data. By using a test set, the model’s predictions remain unbiased and reliable.
